we're meeting. My name is Ryan Johnson and I'm a data science advisor here at

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:18.719
Posit. So in today's workflow we are going to focus in on PDFs, which is a

00:00:18.719 --> 00:00:22.959
file format we've probably all encountered at some point. Now we're

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:27.559
going to kick off the demo talking about what are PDFs and why are they such a

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:31.840
popular method for sharing documents. And then we'll jump into the actual

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:36.759
demos where we'll demonstrate how to create some really beautiful scalable

00:00:36.759 --> 00:00:41.799
professional PDFs using a combination of Posit's open source tools and our

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:47.200
professional tools. So with that let's go ahead and get started. Alright so just a

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:52.360
few slides here to get started. And the first thing I want to talk about is

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:58.240
what is PDF, which stands for portable document format, particularly why is it

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:03.279
so popular. So if you've ever been in a situation where you had to share a

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:09.000
document with somebody you probably had to stop and think and consider what is

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.040
the optimal format for sharing this document. For example if my documents in

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:19.000
a Microsoft Word document and I want to share it with somebody else you probably

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:23.959
ask some questions to yourself like does that person also have Microsoft Word and

00:01:23.959 --> 00:01:28.480
if so do they have the same version or at least a relatively recent version or

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.519
similar version to what I have. Maybe if they don't have Microsoft Word but also

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:39.440
work in Google Docs we're not sure. So maybe you try a different format and you

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:44.440
want to create an HTML document. So if you go to share an HTML document

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:49.199
with somebody you have a whole new set of questions such as what internet web

00:01:49.199 --> 00:01:52.839
browser will they use to open up this document which is essentially a web page.

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:59.839
Are they going to use Safari, Firefox, Chrome and depending on what browser they

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:06.279
use it may render slightly differently. Now for a lot of these HTML formats they

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:11.960
require some system dependencies such as JavaScript. So if they go to open an HTML

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.800
document and they don't have JavaScript installed will it render appropriately

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:23.119
we don't know. Also if you go to try to email an HTML document to somebody a lot

00:02:23.119 --> 00:02:29.039
of email clients will actually block emails that have HTML files as

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:34.520
attachments so that's something else you need to consider. And then particularly

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:38.679
important for today's demo what if we want to share a document that's created

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:44.720
using something like Jupyter Notebooks or Quarto or R Markdown. So if we go to

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:49.160
share one of these documents does that recipient also have R and Python

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:54.279
installing can they even open up these documents and if so do they have the

00:02:54.279 --> 00:02:58.880
same package versions and language version that I do to ensure that it's

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:03.479
the exact same document and it's rendered the exact same way when they

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:09.240
open it up on their system. So that's a lot of questions to answer and this

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.759
really is the driving force behind why PDFs were created because they are

00:03:14.759 --> 00:03:21.440
perfect for cross-platform compatibility. So if I create a PDF on my Mac

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:25.039
computer and I go to share with somebody using a Windows machine I can be pretty

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:29.679
confident it's gonna render exactly the same because it preserves formatting

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:34.559
which is really important. PDFs is also something known as a what you see is

00:03:34.559 --> 00:03:41.679
what you get format meaning the content won't shift reflow or break apart when

00:03:41.679 --> 00:03:46.839
open on different devices. So unlike formats such as Word where formatting

00:03:46.839 --> 00:03:51.360
can change depending on the software or device things are just going to stay

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:58.679
pretty consistent with PDFs. PDFs are also by default non-editable so if you

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:01.720
go to share with somebody they're really not going to be able to edit it.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.240
Now there are some ways you can edit a PDF but usually by default they're

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:10.039
non-editable and they're also print ready so if you receive a PDF you can

00:04:10.039 --> 00:04:14.919
typically file print and that printed output will look pretty good and there's

00:04:14.919 --> 00:04:21.399
a whole lot of other reasons why PDFs are so popular for sharing documents. Now

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:28.519
most software for creating documents has some type of built-in PDF export option

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:33.239
but when it comes to the creation of specialized documents that include

00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:39.959
things like mathematical equations, symbols, citations, other complex

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:45.640
structures like chapters, sections, table of contents, journal formats for example,

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:50.559
complex tables and figures, chances are you're likely going to come across a

00:04:50.559 --> 00:04:58.799
tool called LaTeX. Now in full disclosure I have never wrote LaTeX code

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:03.359
so I can't speak too much to how complex it is but from what I heard it is a

00:05:03.359 --> 00:05:09.399
fantastic tool but it does have some complications and limitations. Now

00:05:09.399 --> 00:05:14.079
fortunately many of the open source tools that we'll work with today have

00:05:14.079 --> 00:05:19.279
methods to create PDFs without ever having to know how to code in LaTeX but

00:05:19.279 --> 00:05:23.399
there are some newer tools out there for creating PDFs which we'll discuss

